2236     def atomic_move(self, src, dest, unsafe_writes=False):
2237         '''atomically move src to dest, copying attributes from dest, returns true on success
2238         it uses os.rename to ensure this as it is an atomic operation, rest of the function is
2239         to work around limitations, corner cases and ensure selinux context is saved if possible'''
2240         context = None
2241         dest_stat = None
2242         b_src = to_bytes(src, errors='surrogate_or_strict')
2243         b_dest = to_bytes(dest, errors='surrogate_or_strict')
2244         if os.path.exists(b_dest):
2245             try:
2246                 dest_stat = os.stat(b_dest)
2247 
2248                 # copy mode and ownership
2249                 os.chmod(b_src, dest_stat.st_mode & PERM_BITS)
2250                 os.chown(b_src, dest_stat.st_uid, dest_stat.st_gid)
2251 
2252                 # try to copy flags if possible
2253                 if hasattr(os, 'chflags') and hasattr(dest_stat, 'st_flags'):
2254                     try:
2255                         os.chflags(b_src, dest_stat.st_flags)
2256                     except OSError as e:
2257                         for err in 'EOPNOTSUPP', 'ENOTSUP':
2258                             if hasattr(errno, err) and e.errno == getattr(errno, err):
2259                                 break
2260                         else:
2261                             raise
2262             except OSError as e:
2263                 if e.errno != errno.EPERM:
2264                     raise
2265             if self.selinux_enabled():
2266                 context = self.selinux_context(dest)
2267         else:
2268             if self.selinux_enabled():
2269                 context = self.selinux_default_context(dest)
2270 
2271         creating = not os.path.exists(b_dest)
2272 
2273         try:
2274             # Optimistically try a rename, solves some corner cases and can avoid useless work, throws exception if not atomic.
2275             os.rename(b_src, b_dest)
2276         except (IOError, OSError) as e:
2277             if e.errno not in [errno.EPERM, errno.EXDEV, errno.EACCES, errno.ETXTBSY, errno.EBUSY]:
2278                 # only try workarounds for errno 18 (cross device), 1 (not permitted),  13 (permission denied)
2279                 # and 26 (text file busy) which happens on vagrant synced folders and other 'exotic' non posix file systems
2280                 self.fail_json(msg='Could not replace file: %s to %s: %s' % (src, dest, to_native(e)),
2281                                exception=traceback.format_exc())
2282             else:
2283                 # Use bytes here.  In the shippable CI, this fails with
2284                 # a UnicodeError with surrogateescape'd strings for an unknown
2285                 # reason (doesn't happen in a local Ubuntu16.04 VM)
2286                 b_dest_dir = os.path.dirname(b_dest)
2287                 b_suffix = os.path.basename(b_dest)
2288                 error_msg = None
2289                 tmp_dest_name = None
2290                 try:
2291                     tmp_dest_fd, tmp_dest_name = tempfile.mkstemp(prefix=b'.ansible_tmp',
2292                                                                   dir=b_dest_dir, suffix=b_suffix)
2293                 except (OSError, IOError) as e:
2294                     error_msg = 'The destination directory (%s) is not writable by the current user. Error was: %s' % (os.path.dirname(dest), to_native(e))
2295                 except TypeError:
2296                     # We expect that this is happening because python3.4.x and
2297                     # below can't handle byte strings in mkstemp().  Traceback
2298                     # would end in something like:
2299                     #     file = _os.path.join(dir, pre + name + suf)
2300                     # TypeError: can't concat bytes to str
2301                     error_msg = ('Failed creating tmp file for atomic move.  This usually happens when using Python3 less than Python3.5. '
2302                                  'Please use Python2.x or Python3.5 or greater.')
2303                 finally:
2304                     if error_msg:
2305                         if unsafe_writes:
2306                             self._unsafe_writes(b_src, b_dest)
2307                         else:
2308                             self.fail_json(msg=error_msg, exception=traceback.format_exc())
2309 
2310                 if tmp_dest_name:
2311                     b_tmp_dest_name = to_bytes(tmp_dest_name, errors='surrogate_or_strict')
2312 
2313                     try:
2314                         try:
2315                             # close tmp file handle before file operations to prevent text file busy errors on vboxfs synced folders (windows host)
2316                             os.close(tmp_dest_fd)
2317                             # leaves tmp file behind when sudo and not root
2318                             try:
2319                                 shutil.move(b_src, b_tmp_dest_name)
2320                             except OSError:
2321                                 # cleanup will happen by 'rm' of tmpdir
2322                                 # copy2 will preserve some metadata
2323                                 shutil.copy2(b_src, b_tmp_dest_name)
2324 
2325                             if self.selinux_enabled():
2326                                 self.set_context_if_different(
2327                                     b_tmp_dest_name, context, False)
2328                             try:
2329                                 tmp_stat = os.stat(b_tmp_dest_name)
2330                                 if dest_stat and (tmp_stat.st_uid != dest_stat.st_uid or tmp_stat.st_gid != dest_stat.st_gid):
2331                                     os.chown(b_tmp_dest_name, dest_stat.st_uid, dest_stat.st_gid)
2332                             except OSError as e:
2333                                 if e.errno != errno.EPERM:
2334                                     raise
2335                             try:
2336                                 os.rename(b_tmp_dest_name, b_dest)
2337                             except (shutil.Error, OSError, IOError) as e:
2338                                 if unsafe_writes and e.errno == errno.EBUSY:
2339                                     self._unsafe_writes(b_tmp_dest_name, b_dest)
2340                                 else:
2341                                     self.fail_json(msg='Unable to make %s into to %s, failed final rename from %s: %s' %
2342                                                        (src, dest, b_tmp_dest_name, to_native(e)),
2343                                                    exception=traceback.format_exc())
2344                         except (shutil.Error, OSError, IOError) as e:
2345                             self.fail_json(msg='Failed to replace file: %s to %s: %s' % (src, dest, to_native(e)),
2346                                            exception=traceback.format_exc())
2347                     finally:
2348                         self.cleanup(b_tmp_dest_name)
2349 
2350         if creating:
2351             # make sure the file has the correct permissions
2352             # based on the current value of umask
2353             umask = os.umask(0)
2354             os.umask(umask)
2355             os.chmod(b_dest, DEFAULT_PERM & ~umask)
2356             try:
2357                 os.chown(b_dest, os.geteuid(), os.getegid())
2358             except OSError:
2359                 # We're okay with trying our best here.  If the user is not
2360                 # root (or old Unices) they won't be able to chown.
2361                 pass
2362 
2363         if self.selinux_enabled():
2364             # rename might not preserve context
2365             self.set_context_if_different(dest, context, False)
2366 
2367     def _unsafe_writes(self, src, dest):
2368         # sadly there are some situations where we cannot ensure atomicity, but only if
2369         # the user insists and we get the appropriate error we update the file unsafely
2370         try:
2371             out_dest = in_src = None
2372             try:
2373                 out_dest = open(dest, 'wb')
2374                 in_src = open(src, 'rb')
2375                 shutil.copyfileobj(in_src, out_dest)
2376             finally:  # assuring closed files in 2.4 compatible way
2377                 if out_dest:
2378                     out_dest.close()
2379                 if in_src:
2380                     in_src.close()
2381         except (shutil.Error, OSError, IOError) as e:
2382             self.fail_json(msg='Could not write data to file (%s) from (%s): %s' % (dest, src, to_native(e)),
2383                            exception=traceback.format_exc())
2384 
2385     def _clean_args(self, args):
2386 
2387         if not self._clean:
2388             # create a printable version of the command for use in reporting later,
2389             # which strips out things like passwords from the args list
2390             to_clean_args = args
2391             if PY2:
2392                 if isinstance(args, text_type):
2393                     to_clean_args = to_bytes(args)
2394             else:
2395                 if isinstance(args, binary_type):
2396                     to_clean_args = to_text(args)
2397             if isinstance(args, (text_type, binary_type)):
2398                 to_clean_args = shlex.split(to_clean_args)
2399 
2400             clean_args = []
2401             is_passwd = False
2402             for arg in (to_native(a) for a in to_clean_args):
2403                 if is_passwd:
2404                     is_passwd = False
2405                     clean_args.append('********')
2406                     continue
2407                 if PASSWD_ARG_RE.match(arg):
2408                     sep_idx = arg.find('=')
2409                     if sep_idx > -1:
2410                         clean_args.append('%s=********' % arg[:sep_idx])
2411                         continue
2412                     else:
2413                         is_passwd = True
2414                 arg = heuristic_log_sanitize(arg, self.no_log_values)
2415                 clean_args.append(arg)
2416             self._clean = ' '.join(shlex_quote(arg) for arg in clean_args)
2417 
2418         return self._clean
2419 
2420     def _restore_signal_handlers(self):
2421         # Reset SIGPIPE to SIG_DFL, otherwise in Python2.7 it gets ignored in subprocesses.
2422         if PY2 and sys.platform != 'win32':
2423             signal.signal(signal.SIGPIPE, signal.SIG_DFL)
2424 
2425     def run_command(self, args, check_rc=False, close_fds=True, executable=None, data=None, binary_data=False, path_prefix=None, cwd=None,
2426                     use_unsafe_shell=False, prompt_regex=None, environ_update=None, umask=None, encoding='utf-8', errors='surrogate_or_strict',
2427                     expand_user_and_vars=True, pass_fds=None, before_communicate_callback=None):
2428         '''
2429         Execute a command, returns rc, stdout, and stderr.
2430 
2431         :arg args: is the command to run
2432             * If args is a list, the command will be run with shell=False.
2433             * If args is a string and use_unsafe_shell=False it will split args to a list and run with shell=False
2434             * If args is a string and use_unsafe_shell=True it runs with shell=True.
2435         :kw check_rc: Whether to call fail_json in case of non zero RC.
2436             Default False
2437         :kw close_fds: See documentation for subprocess.Popen(). Default True
2438         :kw executable: See documentation for subprocess.Popen(). Default None
2439         :kw data: If given, information to write to the stdin of the command
2440         :kw binary_data: If False, append a newline to the data.  Default False
2441         :kw path_prefix: If given, additional path to find the command in.
2442             This adds to the PATH environment variable so helper commands in
2443             the same directory can also be found
2444         :kw cwd: If given, working directory to run the command inside
2445         :kw use_unsafe_shell: See `args` parameter.  Default False
2446         :kw prompt_regex: Regex string (not a compiled regex) which can be
2447             used to detect prompts in the stdout which would otherwise cause
2448             the execution to hang (especially if no input data is specified)
2449         :kw environ_update: dictionary to *update* os.environ with
2450         :kw umask: Umask to be used when running the command. Default None
2451         :kw encoding: Since we return native strings, on python3 we need to
2452             know the encoding to use to transform from bytes to text.  If you
2453             want to always get bytes back, use encoding=None.  The default is
2454             "utf-8".  This does not affect transformation of strings given as
2455             args.
2456         :kw errors: Since we return native strings, on python3 we need to
2457             transform stdout and stderr from bytes to text.  If the bytes are
2458             undecodable in the ``encoding`` specified, then use this error
2459             handler to deal with them.  The default is ``surrogate_or_strict``
2460             which means that the bytes will be decoded using the
2461             surrogateescape error handler if available (available on all
2462             python3 versions we support) otherwise a UnicodeError traceback
2463             will be raised.  This does not affect transformations of strings
2464             given as args.
2465         :kw expand_user_and_vars: When ``use_unsafe_shell=False`` this argument
2466             dictates whether ``~`` is expanded in paths and environment variables
2467             are expanded before running the command. When ``True`` a string such as
2468             ``$SHELL`` will be expanded regardless of escaping. When ``False`` and
2469             ``use_unsafe_shell=False`` no path or variable expansion will be done.
2470         :kw pass_fds: When running on Python 3 this argument
2471             dictates which file descriptors should be passed
2472             to an underlying ``Popen`` constructor. On Python 2, this will
2473             set ``close_fds`` to False.
2474         :kw before_communicate_callback: This function will be called
2475             after ``Popen`` object will be created
2476             but before communicating to the process.
2477             (``Popen`` object will be passed to callback as a first argument)
2478         :returns: A 3-tuple of return code (integer), stdout (native string),
2479             and stderr (native string).  On python2, stdout and stderr are both
2480             byte strings.  On python3, stdout and stderr are text strings converted
2481             according to the encoding and errors parameters.  If you want byte
2482             strings on python3, use encoding=None to turn decoding to text off.
2483         '''
2484         # used by clean args later on
2485         self._clean = None
2486 
2487         if not isinstance(args, (list, binary_type, text_type)):
2488             msg = "Argument 'args' to run_command must be list or string"
2489             self.fail_json(rc=257, cmd=args, msg=msg)
2490 
2491         shell = False
2492         if use_unsafe_shell:
2493 
2494             # stringify args for unsafe/direct shell usage
2495             if isinstance(args, list):
2496                 args = b" ".join([to_bytes(shlex_quote(x), errors='surrogate_or_strict') for x in args])
2497             else:
2498                 args = to_bytes(args, errors='surrogate_or_strict')
2499 
2500             # not set explicitly, check if set by controller
2501             if executable:
2502                 executable = to_bytes(executable, errors='surrogate_or_strict')
2503                 args = [executable, b'-c', args]
2504             elif self._shell not in (None, '/bin/sh'):
2505                 args = [to_bytes(self._shell, errors='surrogate_or_strict'), b'-c', args]
2506             else:
2507                 shell = True
2508         else:
2509             # ensure args are a list
2510             if isinstance(args, (binary_type, text_type)):
2511                 # On python2.6 and below, shlex has problems with text type
2512                 # On python3, shlex needs a text type.
2513                 if PY2:
2514                     args = to_bytes(args, errors='surrogate_or_strict')
2515                 elif PY3:
2516                     args = to_text(args, errors='surrogateescape')
2517                 args = shlex.split(args)
2518 
2519             # expand ``~`` in paths, and all environment vars
2520             if expand_user_and_vars:
2521                 args = [to_bytes(os.path.expanduser(os.path.expandvars(x)), errors='surrogate_or_strict') for x in args if x is not None]
2522             else:
2523                 args = [to_bytes(x, errors='surrogate_or_strict') for x in args if x is not None]
2524 
2525         prompt_re = None
2526         if prompt_regex:
2527             if isinstance(prompt_regex, text_type):
2528                 if PY3:
2529                     prompt_regex = to_bytes(prompt_regex, errors='surrogateescape')
2530                 elif PY2:
2531                     prompt_regex = to_bytes(prompt_regex, errors='surrogate_or_strict')
2532             try:
2533                 prompt_re = re.compile(prompt_regex, re.MULTILINE)
2534             except re.error:
2535                 self.fail_json(msg="invalid prompt regular expression given to run_command")
2536 
2537         rc = 0
2538         msg = None
2539         st_in = None
2540 
2541         # Manipulate the environ we'll send to the new process
2542         old_env_vals = {}
2543         # We can set this from both an attribute and per call
2544         for key, val in self.run_command_environ_update.items():
2545             old_env_vals[key] = os.environ.get(key, None)
2546             os.environ[key] = val
2547         if environ_update:
2548             for key, val in environ_update.items():
2549                 old_env_vals[key] = os.environ.get(key, None)
2550                 os.environ[key] = val
2551         if path_prefix:
2552             old_env_vals['PATH'] = os.environ['PATH']
2553             os.environ['PATH'] = "%s:%s" % (path_prefix, os.environ['PATH'])
2554 
2555         # If using test-module.py and explode, the remote lib path will resemble:
2556         #   /tmp/test_module_scratch/debug_dir/ansible/module_utils/basic.py
2557         # If using ansible or ansible-playbook with a remote system:
2558         #   /tmp/ansible_vmweLQ/ansible_modlib.zip/ansible/module_utils/basic.py
2559 
2560         # Clean out python paths set by ansiballz
2561         if 'PYTHONPATH' in os.environ:
2562             pypaths = os.environ['PYTHONPATH'].split(':')
2563             pypaths = [x for x in pypaths
2564                        if not x.endswith('/ansible_modlib.zip') and
2565                        not x.endswith('/debug_dir')]
2566             os.environ['PYTHONPATH'] = ':'.join(pypaths)
2567             if not os.environ['PYTHONPATH']:
2568                 del os.environ['PYTHONPATH']
2569 
2570         if data:
2571             st_in = subprocess.PIPE
2572 
2573         kwargs = dict(
2574             executable=executable,
2575             shell=shell,
2576             close_fds=close_fds,
2577             stdin=st_in,
2578             stdout=subprocess.PIPE,
2579             stderr=subprocess.PIPE,
2580             preexec_fn=self._restore_signal_handlers,
2581         )
2582         if PY3 and pass_fds:
2583             kwargs["pass_fds"] = pass_fds
2584         elif PY2 and pass_fds:
2585             kwargs['close_fds'] = False
2586 
2587         # store the pwd
2588         prev_dir = os.getcwd()
2589 
2590         # make sure we're in the right working directory
2591         if cwd and os.path.isdir(cwd):
2592             cwd = to_bytes(os.path.abspath(os.path.expanduser(cwd)), errors='surrogate_or_strict')
2593             kwargs['cwd'] = cwd
2594             try:
2595                 os.chdir(cwd)
2596             except (OSError, IOError) as e:
2597                 self.fail_json(rc=e.errno, msg="Could not open %s, %s" % (cwd, to_native(e)),
2598                                exception=traceback.format_exc())
2599 
2600         old_umask = None
2601         if umask:
2602             old_umask = os.umask(umask)
2603 
2604         try:
2605             if self._debug:
2606                 self.log('Executing: ' + self._clean_args(args))
2607             cmd = subprocess.Popen(args, **kwargs)
2608             if before_communicate_callback:
2609                 before_communicate_callback(cmd)
2610 
2611             # the communication logic here is essentially taken from that
2612             # of the _communicate() function in ssh.py
2613 
2614             stdout = b''
2615             stderr = b''
2616             selector = selectors.DefaultSelector()
2617             selector.register(cmd.stdout, selectors.EVENT_READ)
2618             selector.register(cmd.stderr, selectors.EVENT_READ)
2619             if os.name == 'posix':
2620                 fcntl.fcntl(cmd.stdout.fileno(), fcntl.F_SETFL, fcntl.fcntl(cmd.stdout.fileno(), fcntl.F_GETFL) | os.O_NONBLOCK)
2621                 fcntl.fcntl(cmd.stderr.fileno(), fcntl.F_SETFL, fcntl.fcntl(cmd.stderr.fileno(), fcntl.F_GETFL) | os.O_NONBLOCK)
2622 
2623             if data:
2624                 if not binary_data:
2625                     data += '\n'
2626                 if isinstance(data, text_type):
2627                     data = to_bytes(data)
2628                 cmd.stdin.write(data)
2629                 cmd.stdin.close()
2630 
2631             while True:
2632                 events = selector.select(1)
2633                 for key, event in events:
2634                     b_chunk = key.fileobj.read()
2635                     if b_chunk == b(''):
2636                         selector.unregister(key.fileobj)
2637                     if key.fileobj == cmd.stdout:
2638                         stdout += b_chunk
2639                     elif key.fileobj == cmd.stderr:
2640                         stderr += b_chunk
2641                 # if we're checking for prompts, do it now
2642                 if prompt_re:
2643                     if prompt_re.search(stdout) and not data:
2644                         if encoding:
2645                             stdout = to_native(stdout, encoding=encoding, errors=errors)
2646                         return (257, stdout, "A prompt was encountered while running a command, but no input data was specified")
2647                 # only break out if no pipes are left to read or
2648                 # the pipes are completely read and
2649                 # the process is terminated
2650                 if (not events or not selector.get_map()) and cmd.poll() is not None:
2651                     break
2652                 # No pipes are left to read but process is not yet terminated
2653                 # Only then it is safe to wait for the process to be finished
2654                 # NOTE: Actually cmd.poll() is always None here if no selectors are left
2655                 elif not selector.get_map() and cmd.poll() is None:
2656                     cmd.wait()
2657                     # The process is terminated. Since no pipes to read from are
2658                     # left, there is no need to call select() again.
2659                     break
2660 
2661             cmd.stdout.close()
2662             cmd.stderr.close()
2663             selector.close()
2664 
2665             rc = cmd.returncode
2666         except (OSError, IOError) as e:
2667             self.log("Error Executing CMD:%s Exception:%s" % (self._clean_args(args), to_native(e)))
2668             self.fail_json(rc=e.errno, msg=to_native(e), cmd=self._clean_args(args))
2669         except Exception as e:
2670             self.log("Error Executing CMD:%s Exception:%s" % (self._clean_args(args), to_native(traceback.format_exc())))
2671             self.fail_json(rc=257, msg=to_native(e), exception=traceback.format_exc(), cmd=self._clean_args(args))
2672 
2673         # Restore env settings
2674         for key, val in old_env_vals.items():
2675             if val is None:
2676                 del os.environ[key]
2677             else:
2678                 os.environ[key] = val
2679 
2680         if old_umask:
2681             os.umask(old_umask)
2682 
2683         if rc != 0 and check_rc:
2684             msg = heuristic_log_sanitize(stderr.rstrip(), self.no_log_values)
2685             self.fail_json(cmd=self._clean_args(args), rc=rc, stdout=stdout, stderr=stderr, msg=msg)
2686 
2687         # reset the pwd
2688         os.chdir(prev_dir)
2689 
2690         if encoding is not None:
2691             return (rc, to_native(stdout, encoding=encoding, errors=errors),
2692                     to_native(stderr, encoding=encoding, errors=errors))
2693 
2694         return (rc, stdout, stderr)
2695

2718     @staticmethod
2719     def get_buffer_size(fd):
2720         try:
2721             # 1032 == FZ_GETPIPE_SZ
2722             buffer_size = fcntl.fcntl(fd, 1032)
2723         except Exception:
2724             try:
2725                 # not as exact as above, but should be good enough for most platforms that fail the previous call
2726                 buffer_size = select.PIPE_BUF
2727             except Exception:
2728                 buffer_size = 9000  # use sane default JIC
2729 
2730         return buffer_size
